  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/27891321?book_show_action=true">Jul 21, 2008</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Scurra" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Scurra" href="/user/show/1350905-scurra">Scurra</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9780446391177" href="/book/show/459744.Adventures_in_the_Screen_Trade">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/1350905-scurra?shelf=non-fiction">non-fiction</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer27891321" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer4634826102315176989">Nobody Knows Anything.<br/><br/>Goldman could almost have saved us the 400-pages of what is still one of the most insightful books about the movie-industry, and just printed his Law on a single page at the front.<br/>But then we&apos;d have missed a glorious roller-coaster ride through Tinseltown stuffed to the gills with anecdotes of such toe-curling detail that you believe every word. <br/>And even now, 25 years later, it still all rings true. Read it, and you too might understand how lucky we are to get the occasiona</span>
  <span id="freeText4634826102315176989" style="display:none">Nobody Knows Anything.<br /><br />Goldman could almost have saved us the 400-pages of what is still one of the most insightful books about the movie-industry, and just printed his Law on a single page at the front.<br />But then we'd have missed a glorious roller-coaster ride through Tinseltown stuffed to the gills with anecdotes of such toe-curling detail that you believe every word. <br />And even now, 25 years later, it still all rings true. Read it, and you too might understand how lucky we are to get the occasional "great" movie. Because it's quite simple:<br /><br />Nobody Knows Anything.</span>
  <a data-text-id="4634826102315176989" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

